article.description:
With the All-Star break only 20 minutes
of basketball away, the Charlotte Sting used all they had to end
the first half of the season on the winning side.
article.headline: Minnesota handed record eighth straight road loss
article.linkText: Sting rally from 13 down late to upend Lynx
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- With the All-Star break only 20 minutes
of basketball away, the Charlotte Sting used all they had to end
the first half of the season on the winning side.

	   The Sting rallied from 13 points down to hand Minnesota its
record eighth-straight road loss with a 63-60 victory over the Lynx
on Saturday night.

	   Allison Feaster made a pair of free throws with 11 seconds left
to seal the win and give Charlotte (11-8) a half-game lead over New
York for second place in the Eastern Conference.

	   ''Down by 13, I told them at the half to expend all their energy
and really get after it to win this game,'' Charlotte coach Anne
Donovan said. ''It was by far our best win of the season. To put
that effort out in the second half speaks volumes for the character
of this team.''

	   Minnesota (6-13) has not won a road game since June 1 and has
just two victories away from home this season. The Lynx had a
chance, though, holding their double-digit lead into the second
half before collapsing late.

	   ''We've been in a lot of close games, unfortunately we've been
on the losing end,'' Minnesota coach Brian Agler said. ''We just
have to start winning games like these, and we've had our
opportunities.''

	   Katie Smith, second in the WNBA in scoring at 18.4 points a
game, had just 13 for Minnesota. She didn't attempt a shot in the
second half until her 3-pointer with 1:01 to play cut Charlotte's
lead to 61-60.

	   Andrea Stinson then missed for Charlotte, giving Minnesota a
chance to win it with a final shot. But Svetlana Abrosimova turned
the ball over when her pass across the court was way too high and
hit the side of the rim.

	   Charlotte got the rebound and after a pair of timeouts,
inbounded the ball to Feaster, who was immediately fouled. She made
both free throws to lock up the win.

	   ''We fought through our fatigue, through our poor shooting and
stuck with a full-court press in the second half,'' Feaster said.
''It worked, we got a much needed win and now we have the next few
days to rest.''

	   Tammy Sutton-Brown led Charlotte with 13 points, and Feaster
scored 12.

	   Abrosimova scored 17 for the Lynx. Smith shot 4-for-11 for
Minnesota and missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer that could have tied
the game.

	   ''I have to find a way to get more involved when they are trying
to limit my touches,'' Smith said. ''I have to try to open things
up more for my teammates when they double me. We just weren't
poised enough to handle their pressure.''

	   Feaster, who leads the league in 3-pointers, missed all four of
her first-half attempts and the Sting shot just 33 percent while
falling into a 33-25 hole at the break.

	   The Sting were lethargic at the start of the second, and
Minnesota pushed its lead to 41-28 with 15:05 to play.

	   Feaster finally got things rolling for Charlotte by hitting a 3
with 14:38 to play -- her eighth straight game with a 3. It sparked
a 23-10 run that gave the Sting their first lead of the game when
Feaster made another 3 with 5:32 to play to put Charlotte up 54-51.

	   Reserve guards Tonya Edwards and Kelly Miller were key during
Charlotte's run, with Edwards scoring six straight points and
coming up with a steal that helped the Sting close to 45-44.

	   After a Minnesota basket and a Charlotte miss, Miller had a
steal, pushed the ball up the court and passed it off so she could
get open. She did, scoring an open 3 that tied it at 47 with 7:43
left.

	   Sutton-Brown, the first Canadian to make the WNBA All-Star Game
when she was chosen as a reserve this week, scored on a pair of
layups to help Charlotte keep pace with Minnesota. The Sting broke
the tie for good on Feaster's 3.
